\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify oxidant for pyruvate\u2192glyoxylate (e.g., Fe(III), MnO\u2082, or photochemical oxidation)\", \"Note that the 2024 PNAS study used nitrate as nitrogen source rather than NH\u2083\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.88,\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.78,\n                \"rxn_019\": 0.85\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.83,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n            \"feedback\": \"ZnS photocatalytic reductive amination of glyoxylate is supported by Wang et al. 2012. The environmental transition from hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis to surface ZnS photocatalysis is plausible (hydrothermal effluent reaching photic zone) but requires transport of glyoxylate to UV-illuminated mineral surfaces. The ZnS band gap (~3.6 eV) is appropriate for near-UV catalysis. Same concern about rxn_006 oxidant as P5.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Justify glyoxylate transport from hydrothermal to surface environment\", \"Specify UV wavelength range for ZnS activation\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.82,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.88\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.87,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n            \"feedback\": \"Cyanosulfidic photochemistry (Patel et al. 2015, Nature Chemistry) is a 