nvironmental_progression\": 0.78,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"Glycolonitrile formation (rxn_017) is well-documented (Schwartz & Goverde 1982; detected in interstellar sources by Zeng et al. 2019). However, glycolonitrile hydrolysis and oxidation to glyoxylic acid (rxn_018) is the weakest step \u2014 it requires both hydrolysis of the nitrile group and oxidation of the alcohol, and the oxidant is unspecified. The final ferroan brucite step is strong. Environmental flow from Surface (rxn_017, rxn_018) to Hydrothermal (rxn_007) is somewhat reversed from the expected Hydrothermal\u2192Surface direction.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify oxidant for glycolonitrile\u2192glyoxylic acid conversion\", \"Consider whether glycolaldehyde would be a more plausible intermediate\", \"Reconsider environmental assignment \u2014 rxn_007 as Hydrothermal but receiving Surface products needs transport justification\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_017\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_018\": 0.72,\n                \"rxn_019\": 0.85\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"Same strengths and weaknesses as P9, but with ZnS photocatalysis replacing ferroan brucite for the final step. The environmental coherence is slightly better here since all steps are Surface-labeled, maintaining consistency. The glycolonitrile\u2192glyoxylic acid step remains the bottleneck requiring oxidant specification.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify oxidant for glycolonitrile\u2192glyoxylic acid\", \"Consider UV-mediated oxidation on mineral surfaces as a possible mechanism\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is an outstanding prebiotic synthesis network for glycine that demonstrates exceptional alignment with current literature. The network successfully integrates 10 distinct pathways across three environments, anchored by 5 well-chosen hub molecules (HCN, HCHO, aminoacetonitrile, glyoxylic acid, NH\u2083). Key strengths: (1) Excellent literature grounding \u2014 the Strecker, Bucherer-Bergs, HCN polymer, cyanosulfidic, FTT, ferroan brucite, and ZnS photocatalysis routes are all supported by specific experimental studies cited in the research; (2) Strong convergent topology with shared intermediates creating redundancy; (3) Proper environmental stratification with hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation feeding surface chemistry feeding biochemical hydrolysis; (4) All mineral catalysts (greigite, magnetite, awaruite, ferroan brucite, ZnS) are geologically plausible and experimentally validated. Minor concerns: (a) rxn_005 (formate\u2192HCHO) and rxn_018 (glycolonitrile\u2192glyoxylic acid) lack sufficient mechanistic detail and oxidant specification; (b) rxn_016 oversimplifies the cyanosulfidic mechanism (should note Cu/phosphate/UV requirements); (c) HCN and NH\u2083 are listed as hub/starting materials without explicit synthesis reactions (atmospheric spark/UV sources should be included for completeness); (d) The HCN concentration problem is not addressed for rxn_014. Despite these issues, the network represents a scientifically rigorous and well-structured synthesis plan that captures the essential features of prebiotic glycine chemistry as understood in current literature.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.93,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.92\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluat