her this step requires specific mineral surface or pH conditions"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.9, "rxn_004": 0.85, "rxn_008": 0.92, "rxn_009": 0.93, "rxn_012": 0.9, "rxn_013": 0.88}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.89, "pathway_coherence": 0.92, "environmental_progression": 0.88, "target_achievement": 0.93, "overall_confidence": 0.9, "feedback": "Bucherer-Bergs pathway is strongly supported by Taillades et al. 1998 and Pulletikurti et al. 2022 (80% hydantoin yield). Literature shows that under realistic prebiotic conditions with excess CO\u2082, the Bucherer-Bergs route through hydantoin can be more productive than direct Strecker hydrolysis, since CO\u2082 catalyzes conversion of even trace aminoacetonitrile to hydantoin, shifting equilibrium productively. The CO\u2082 incorporation step is elegant given its atmospheric abundance. Hydantoin hydrolysis appropriately placed in biochemical (aqueous, mild) environment.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Could note N-carbamoyl-glycine as an explicit intermediate between hydantoin and glycine"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_014": 0.8, "rxn_015": 0.82}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.78, "pathway_coherence": 0.82, "environmental_progression": 0.7, "target_achievement": 0.85, "overall_confidence": 0.8, "feedback": "HCN polymer hydrolysis is well-documented (Ruiz-Bermejo et al. 2013: glycine is the most abundant product under all 23 conditions tested). However, the critical concentration threshold (0.01\u20130.1 M HCN, Sanchez et al. 1967) is not addressed \u2014 oceanic HCN at 100\u00b0C/pH 8 is only ~7\u00d710\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 M (Miyakawa et al. 2002). The eutectic freezing mechanism (\u221223.4\u00b0C, 74.5 mol% HCN) or other concentration mechanisms should be invoked. Both steps labeled Surface, but no mineral catalyst specified; environmental progression is limited (no Hydrothermal\u2192Surface flow within this pathway). Pathway is simple but valid.", "