dehyde (e.g., formate reduction on mineral surfaces) to close the formate dead-end\", \"Clarify which hydrothermal product specifically feeds the Strecker pathway\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.85\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"HCN polymer hydrolysis is well-documented (Ruiz-Bermejo et al. 2013, Or\u00f3 1960s). The pathway correctly identifies eutectic freezing concentration as critical. Glycine is the most abundant product under all tested conditions. The environmental progression (Surface \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical) is somewhat flat \u2014 the eutectic freezing step could be more explicitly characterized as a distinct environmental regime. The concentration threshold of 0.01-0.1 M HCN is a known bottleneck that is appropriately addressed.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Consider adding explicit eutectic freezing conditions (-23.4\u00b0C, 74.5 mol% HCN) to rxn_010 description\", \"Could note that glycine is the most abundant amino acid from polymer hydrolysis\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n            \"feedback\": \"The cyanosulfidic pathway based on Patel et al. (2015) is conceptually sound. rxn_012 significantly simplifies the actual mechanism, which involves Cu(I)-Cu(II) photoredox cycling, phosphate buffer, and UV light at 35\u00b0C, producing aminoacetonitrile among other products. The simplification HCN + H\u2082S \u2192 aminoacetonitrile omits these critical co-factors. The pathway from aminoacetonitrile to glycine via hydrolysis is well-supported. The 3-step count suggests rxn_001 \u2192 rxn_012 \u2192 rxn_006/rxn_007, but the connection from aminoacetonitrile to glycine requires two hydrolysis steps.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add Cu(I)/Cu(II) and phosphate as co-catalysts in rxn_012\", \"Clarify whether pathway includes both rxn_006 and rxn_007 for complete hydrolysis\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.78\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.70,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n            \"feedback\": \"The single-step Fischer-Tropsch synthesis (Yoshino et al. 1971) is experimentally supported but represents the weakest pathway. The direct conversion CO + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 glycine on meteoritic iron at 360-600\u00b0C is mechanistically a surface-mediated multistep process compressed into one reaction node. The single hydrothermal step lacks environmental progression. The literature notes that the actual mechanism likely involves FTT generation of HCHO and HCN on catalyst surfaces followed by Strecker synthesis in cooler zones \u2014 so this 'direct' synthesis is really a compressed Strecker variant.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Decompose into at least two steps: FTT generation of intermediates on catalyst surface, then Strecker synthesis in aqueous phase\", \"Add temperature specification (360-600\u00b0C) and catalyst (meteoritic iron/FeNi) details\", \"Consider adding environmental transition from hydrothermal to surface/aqueous\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_015\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n            \"feedback\": \"This pathway nicely incorporates the landmark 2024 PNAS ferroan brucite study. The progression from formaldehyde self-condensation (formose-type) to glycolaldehyde photooxidation to reductive amination on ferroan brucite is creative and well-supported. The Surface \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal environmental flow is justified. The ferroan brucite result showing 97% glycine partitioning to mineral fraction is particularly significant. rxn_014 could use more detail on base catalysis required for formose-type condensation.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify base catalyst or mineral surface for formose-type self-condensation in rxn_014\", \"Note that NH\u2083 source needs specification for rxn_016 \u2014 where does it come from in this pathway?\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_015\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_017\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"Parallel to P7 but using ZnS photocatalysis (Wang et al. 2012) instead of ferroan brucite. The ZnS-mediated reversible amination of glyoxylate mimicking amino acid dehydrogenase is elegant and well-cited. All Surface environment is slightly less interesting from an environmental interconnection standpoint compared to P7, but chemically equally valid. ZnS band gap (3.6 eV) is appropriate for UV-driven chemistry.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Same formose condensation concerns as P7\", \"Specify UV wavelength requirements for ZnS activation\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_018\": 0.95,\n                \"rxn_019\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_020\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.87,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.87,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n            \"feedback\": \"A creative pathway linking cyanohydrin chemistry to the ferroan brucite reductive amination endpoint. Glycolonitrile formation (rxn_018) is one of the best-established prebiotic reactions (Schwartz & Goverde 1982 showed it also accelerates HCN oligomerization 5-fold). The progression through glycolic acid and glyoxylic acid provides an alternative route to the same glyoxylic acid hub that feeds P7 and P8. The Surface \u2192 Surface \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal flow is well-structured. NH\u2083 source for rxn_016 should be explicitly traced.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Explicitly connect NH\u2083 source to rxn_016 in this pathway\", \"Note literature support from Zeng et al. (2019