or cited study (Miller 1953, Preiner et al. 2020, Beyazay et al. 2023, Taillades et al. 1998, Patel et al. 2015, Wang et al. 2012, Yoshino et al. 1971, 2024 PNAS ferroan brucite) is explicitly represented in the reaction network. (4) Multiple convergence points where different pathways share intermediates, particularly aminoacetonitrile (fed by both Strecker and cyanosulfidic routes) and glyoxylic acid (reached via glycolaldehyde oxidation and glycolonitrile hydrolysis/oxidation). Minor issues: (a) Formate (mol_014) is a dead-end \u2014 produced by rxn_002 but never consumed, representing a minor topology gap. (b) rxn_001 is labeled 'Surface' but represents atmospheric spark discharge. (c) rxn_012 and rxn_013 oversimplify their respective mechanisms. (d) P6 (single-step FTT) is the weakest pathway and falls below the approval threshold. (e) rxn_009 conflates two sequential hydrolysis steps. Despite these minor issues, the network represents a near-optimal computational representation of the prebiotic glycine synthesis landscape.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.93,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.91\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.85, "rxn_004": 0.95, "rxn_005": 0.95, "rxn_006": 0.9, "rxn_007": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.92, "pathway_coherence": 0.95, "environmental_progression": 0.85, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.92, "feedback": "The classic Strecker pathway is the best-supported route in the network, directly mirroring Miller's 1953 mechanism. All four Strecker steps are faithfully represented with correct intermediates (methanimine, aminoacetonitrile, glycinamide). The rate-limiting amide hydrolysis (31 kcal/mol barrier per Magrino et al. 2021) is properly identified. The only minor issue is that rxn_001 is labeled 'Surface' when it represents atmospheric spark discharge; however, the products dissolve into surface/aqueous environments so this is 